From: willis@pogo.eos.ncsu.edu (Bill Willis)
Subject: Re: Merry $*!@ing Christmas!
Reply-To: willis@eos.ncsu.edu
Date: Tue, 7 Dec 1993 14:13:19 GMT




In article <MARCA.93Dec7024328@wintermute.ncsa.uiuc.edu>, marca@ncsa.uiuc.edu (Marc Andreessen) writes:
|>Summary: we are doing our jobs; we are responding to the needs of our
|>target audience; you do not get to tell us what to do simply because
|>you are a citizen and we are (partially) publicly funded.
|>

Amen....

In the midst of this totally insane discussion and despite the fact that the
OSF lawyers are the most difficult people to deal with in my professional
career (well maybe except for the accounting people at CA), I would like to
make a few simple points:

Mosaic is an exceptionally well designed application and is almost perfectly
targeted. It is impacting our world in ways more important than all the
previous free stuff that computer weenies -- including me 8-) -- have done,
used, etc. I applaud the work done at NCSA and hope like hell it continues.

In terms of their choice of Motif, there was simply no other rational choice.
In the GUI world it isn't good enough to have a good look and feel, it has to
be the same look and feel as the other tools you use. Almost every commercial
tool for X11 is Motif or going to be Motif. Anyone who suggests that this was
a poor choice has no grip on the thousands of "just plain users" that folks
like me have to consider.

I do not want to depend on somebody's spare time project designed with the
highest priority on eliminating any possibility of a royalty. I want a well
designed application built to fit in with everything else that I have to use.
I believe that I can depend on Mosaic and the information system strategies we
are taking will depend on Mosaic. Keep at it guys...

Dr. Bill Willis
Associate Provost for Academic Computing
North Carolina State University.

ps. I would like a single resource that let me set the font family/size used in
the html widget without having to set all of the fonts individually... 


