From: hpa@ahab.eecs.nwu.edu (H. Peter Anvin N9ITP)
Subject: Re: Lots more stats in /proc aka /proc/loadavg
Reply-To: hpa@nwu.edu (H. Peter Anvin)
Date: Tue, 7 Dec 1993 19:13:03 GMT

In article <QUANSTRO.93Dec7090348@zeta.eecs.nwu.edu> of
comp.os.linux.development, quanstro@zeta.eecs.nwu.edu (goon) writes:
>
> why do we need to stick this in /proc?
> how about putting this information in /stat?
> 

(Do we need to go through this tread again...?)  The kernel has code
for handling a single information filesystem.  Since its initial
purpose was to aid debugging by showing process statistics, it was
named to "process filesystem" and mounted on /proc.  Then someone
thought about adding system-wide statistics, and realized a lot of the
same code could be used, so he added it to the same file system to
avoid unneccesary kernel bloat.

Besides, having a single mount point gives users less opportunity to
be "creative" and screw things up.  There is already a lot of programs
who have /proc/... as a hardcoded path which fails if you mount it on,
say, /sys.  Imagine four or five info-filesystems, all which can break
a program if they are mis- or unmounted.

        /hpa

